2 Therefore we may slay such persons on our own soil, on the hostile soil, on ground which is no one's, and on the sea. That it is not lawful to slay them, or do them violence, in a peaceful neutral territory, is a consequence, not of their personal rights, but of the rights of the lord of the territory. For civil societies may establish a rule that, against those who are in any territory, nothing shall be done by violence, except when judicial proceedings have been tried 3 as we have already quoted from Euripides. And when judicial pro- ceedings are in force, then the deserts of persons are regarded, and there is an end of that promiscuous right of doing hai-m, which, as we have said, has been established between enemies. Livy relates that seven ships of war of the Carthaginians were in a port belonging to Syphax, who was then at peace both with the Carthaginians and the Romans3 and that Scipio came with two ships and might have been destroyed by the Carthaginians before they entered the harbour3 but that coming with a brisk wind they struck into the port before the Carthaginians could raise their anchor53 and¹ then, in the port be- longing to the king, the Carthaginians did not venture to attack them.
